SINGAPORE DAYBOOK: Hyflux, Keppel, Banyan Tree, Neptune Orient

-- B y   J a n   D a h i n t e n   a n d   P h o e b e   S e d g m a n
-- 
2011-03-07T22:16:41Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-03-07/singapore-daybook-hyflux-keppel-banyan-tree-neptune-orient.html
Hyflux Ltd., a water-treatment
company, was chosen by  Singapore ’s water utility as the
preferred bidder for the city’s second and largest water
desalination plant, a deal valued at S$890 million ($703
million). The award would come with a 25-year management
contract.  MARKETS:  *The MSCI Asia Pacific Index fell 0.9 percent at yesterday’s
close.
*Singapore’s Straits Times Index rose 0.2 percent at yesterday’s
close.
*The  Dow Jones Industrial Average  fell 0.7 percent at
yesterday’s close.
*The Stoxx Europe 600 Index declined 0.4 percent at yesterday’s
close.  EQUITY MOVERS:  *Banyan Tree Holdings Ltd. (BTH SP): The Singapore-based hotel
operator said it is raising S$70 million ($55.3 million),
issuing notes due in 2014. The notes carry a coupon rate of 5.5
percent.
*City Developments Ltd. (CIT SP): Singapore’s second-largest
developer said it sold 150 residential units at its H2O
Residences project in northeast Singapore at an average price of
S$920 per square foot. The project will have 521 apartment units
when completed, it said.
*Hyflux Ltd. (HYF SP): Singapore’s biggest provider of water-
treatment services said the city’s water utility chose the
company as the preferred bidder for its second and largest water
desalination plant. The project will cost S$890 million to build
and come with a 25-year  management contract , it said.
*Keppel Corp. (KEP SP): The world’s largest maker of oil rigs
said a unit won a contract, valued at about $195 million, to
build a repeat jack-up drilling rig for  Mexico ’s Perforadora
Central SA de CV.
*Neptune Orient Lines Ltd. (NOL SP):  Southeast Asia ’s biggest
container carrier said average freight rates climbed 10 percent
in the five weeks to Feb. 11 from a year ago as it handled 5
percent more cargo during the period.  BTV: Guests with times  *7:10 a.m.: Alembic Global Advisors Founder Hassan Ahmed
*7:40 a.m.: Wells Chief Investment Strategist James W. Paulsen
*7:50 a.m.: Pepsi Co. Asia-Pacific President Umram Beba
*8:10 a.m.: CEIBS Economics Professor Wang Jianmao
*8:40 a.m.: Rabobank Agricultural Analyst Wayne Gordon
*9:10 a.m.: Boeing V-P Marketing Randy Tinseth
*9:40 a.m.: StanChart Head of China Research Stephen Green
